06:36.938 --> 06:38.440
Elena?

06:40.233 --> 06:41.906
You okay, Elena?

06:49.618 --> 06:51.871
Frank Sutter's been arrested?

06:52.037 --> 06:54.085
Yes.

06:54.247 --> 06:55.464
What for?

06:57.876 --> 07:00.675
I don't know.
They wouldn't tell me.

07:02.005 --> 07:04.554
In here?

07:04.716 --> 07:06.935
Yes.
What was he doing

07:07.093 --> 07:08.811
in here?

07:11.139 --> 07:13.312
He was having a shower.

07:13.475 --> 07:16.775
They arrested him
while he was in your shower?

07:16.937 --> 07:18.280
Mm-hmm.
Naked?

07:18.438 --> 07:19.530
Yeah, of course

07:19.689 --> 07:20.736
he was naked.

07:20.899 --> 07:22.401
He was in the shower.

07:22.567 --> 07:24.035
Okay.
Of course!

07:26.988 --> 07:28.160
Okay.

07:28.323 --> 07:30.451
It's gonna be okay.
Are you all right?

07:36.414 --> 07:38.257
Hey, hey.

07:38.416 --> 07:40.293
It's... all right.
It'll be all right.

07:43.046 --> 07:44.423
Shirley, please.

07:44.589 --> 07:46.136
Please.

07:46.299 --> 07:47.551
Believe me...

07:47.717 --> 07:49.560
you don't know anything.

07:49.719 --> 07:51.346
This is very bad.

07:51.513 --> 07:54.312
It's bad for Frank, and
it's bad for me, too.

07:54.474 --> 07:56.852
Elena, what have you done?

08:02.107 --> 08:03.529
Hey.

08:05.485 --> 08:08.614
- Is it tender there?
- A little bit.

08:08.780 --> 08:11.033
I'm just going to look
into your eyes.

08:17.789 --> 08:20.167
Stay there.

08:28.842 --> 08:31.436
Does he have
to be handcuffed?

08:31.594 --> 08:33.972
I arrested him on
suspicion of murder.

08:34.139 --> 08:35.561
He resisted arrest.

08:35.724 --> 08:37.726
The murder
of Charlie Stoddart?

08:37.892 --> 08:39.735
And you punched him?

08:39.894 --> 08:41.020
That's right.

08:41.187 --> 08:43.110
How many times
did you punch him?

08:43.273 --> 08:45.025
A number of times.

08:45.191 --> 08:47.193
Hard blows?

08:47.360 --> 08:48.282
Hard enough.

08:48.445 --> 08:49.913
Did he defend himself?

08:52.115 --> 08:54.163
What do you mean?

08:54.325 --> 08:57.795
Was he insensible
when you punched him?

08:57.954 --> 09:00.798
Did his head rotate sharply?

09:00.957 --> 09:03.801
He hit his head
against the wall--

09:03.960 --> 09:05.212
also hard--

09:05.378 --> 09:07.096
when I punched him.

09:19.350 --> 09:20.772
You fucker!

09:24.689 --> 09:26.612
That fucker attacked me.

09:27.942 --> 09:29.819
You have to leave.

09:38.620 --> 09:40.463
<i>He reacted.</i>

09:40.622 --> 09:42.670
He resisted.

09:42.832 --> 09:44.675
No, he reacted.

09:44.834 --> 09:46.836
He was naked.
He was in the shower.

09:47.003 --> 09:48.880
Sheriff Anderssen
barged in.

09:49.047 --> 09:50.344
He reacted.

09:50.507 --> 09:52.009
Resisted.

09:52.175 --> 09:54.052
He was punched and
shoved repeatedly.

09:54.219 --> 09:56.472
No formal caution was made.
You can't be sure about this.

09:56.638 --> 09:58.481
Yes, I can-- I was there;
I witnessed it.

09:58.640 --> 10:00.813
I saw the whole thing.
This is a car crash.

10:00.975 --> 10:02.602
Professor Stoddart

10:02.769 --> 10:04.521
was hacked apart.

10:04.687 --> 10:06.530
If Dan had justification

10:06.689 --> 10:08.783
for suspecting
Frank Sutter did that,

10:08.942 --> 10:10.444
then he had good reason to use

10:10.610 --> 10:12.112
overwhelming force
in the arrest.

10:12.278 --> 10:14.326
Are you trying to persuade me,
Governor,

10:14.489 --> 10:16.287
or are you rehearsing
for a judge?

10:16.449 --> 10:18.076
Look, if your sheriff

10:18.243 --> 10:19.711
is anywhere near
those interviews,

10:19.869 --> 10:22.839
all the interview evidence
will be deemed inadmissible.

10:22.997 --> 10:25.466
You're a lawyer;
you should know that.

10:27.418 --> 10:29.466
You want to conduct
the interviews.

10:29.629 --> 10:31.097
Yes, I do.

10:49.107 --> 10:53.328
<i>To identify whose blood
is on Frank's T-shirt,</i>

10:53.486 --> 10:55.079
we need to make
a DNA comparison.

10:55.238 --> 10:57.661
I don't have time to send
samples to the mainland.

10:57.824 --> 11:01.169
I don't have the equipment
or the necessary skills.

11:04.581 --> 11:08.006
What about the biology department
at the Research Institute?

11:08.168 --> 11:10.671
Stoddart's department.
They would need tissue

11:10.837 --> 11:12.680
from Professor
Stoddart as well.

11:12.839 --> 11:14.887
An eyebrow follicle--
that is usually

11:15.049 --> 11:17.677
what we send to the forensic
lab on the mainland.

11:17.844 --> 11:19.187
It doesn't hurt

11:19.345 --> 11:22.349
when you yank it
out of the head.

11:22.515 --> 11:24.062
Although, obviously,

11:24.225 --> 11:25.568
in this case...

12:00.136 --> 12:03.185
I made sandwiches
for everyone.

12:03.348 --> 12:04.941
I had to do something.

12:05.099 --> 12:06.191
I know.

12:06.351 --> 12:08.649
You don't know.

12:10.772 --> 12:12.615
Who did you arrest?

12:12.774 --> 12:15.027
At the hotel?

12:15.193 --> 12:17.491
Frank Sutter.

12:19.072 --> 12:20.915
A search and rescue pilot.

12:21.074 --> 12:22.621
Why is he a suspect?

12:24.786 --> 12:27.630
Eric...

12:27.789 --> 12:30.918
Tell me.

12:32.085 --> 12:34.588
I found a garment.

12:34.754 --> 12:37.007
His. Covered in blood.

12:37.173 --> 12:41.019
Look...

12:42.637 --> 12:44.890
...this must be
just about impossible

12:45.056 --> 12:47.275
for you.

13:15.128 --> 13:17.426
♪♪

13:49.078 --> 13:51.376
What are you doing?

13:53.583 --> 13:55.836
We need a DNA sample
from Stoddart.

13:56.002 --> 13:58.471
Match the blood on
the T-shirt to Stoddart,

13:58.629 --> 14:01.303
and we have him.

14:01.466 --> 14:04.060
Good, I'll give that
to Petra.

14:04.218 --> 14:05.891
No.

14:06.054 --> 14:07.556
Chain of evidence, Hildur.

14:07.722 --> 14:10.225
I took the sample, I
give the sample. Dan,

14:10.391 --> 14:11.938
you have to stand aside.

14:12.101 --> 14:14.229
I'm not going to stand aside.

14:14.395 --> 14:15.647
Morton will do the interviews.

14:15.813 --> 14:17.611
You can't be present.

14:17.774 --> 14:20.027
You assaulted
Frank Sutter.

14:20.193 --> 14:21.945
He killed Charlie.

14:26.908 --> 14:28.706
If he's the killer,

14:28.868 --> 14:31.462
then he could go free
because of you.

14:31.621 --> 14:33.669
Do you understand this?

15:00.316 --> 15:02.614
Thank you.

15:06.322 --> 15:08.825
There you go.

15:08.991 --> 15:11.494
I'm famished.

15:11.661 --> 15:13.459
Dig in.

15:13.621 --> 15:15.589
Mmm.

15:16.833 --> 15:19.211
You not hungry?
I'm okay.

15:19.377 --> 15:21.755
Do you not like ribs?
No, I do--

15:21.921 --> 15:23.969
totally-- just, today,
they're just a bit too...

15:25.466 --> 15:26.968
...chest cavity.

15:28.136 --> 15:30.685
I'm sorry.

15:30.847 --> 15:31.598
Natalie.

15:31.764 --> 15:33.732
I need you to do

15:33.891 --> 15:36.314
a quantitative PCR
on some fluid stains.

15:36.477 --> 15:38.479
And then a capillary
electrophoresis.

15:38.646 --> 15:39.898
We'd like you to
cross-check it

15:40.064 --> 15:42.112
with the DNA from
an eyebrow follicle.

15:42.275 --> 15:43.618
Is this a blood swab?
Yes.

15:43.776 --> 15:45.028
Whose blood?

15:45.194 --> 15:47.367
That is what we have
to establish and...

15:47.530 --> 15:49.077
as fast as we can.

15:49.240 --> 15:51.789
The professor's?

15:51.951 --> 15:55.000
I'm not allowed to say.

15:55.163 --> 15:58.542
The lab's not forensically
accredited, is it? No.

15:58.708 --> 16:01.131
Any results that we give
you wouldn't be admissible

16:01.294 --> 16:02.967
as evidence.
I understand.

16:03.129 --> 16:05.678
But we just need to know
if there's a blood match.

16:06.841 --> 16:08.468
Five, six hours, tops.

16:08.634 --> 16:10.136
We'll have a result
for you in five.

16:10.303 --> 16:12.522
Okay.

16:16.767 --> 16:19.361
Red wine or white wine?

16:19.520 --> 16:21.648
That is the conundrum.

16:21.814 --> 16:24.067
Exactly. ls it meat or fish?

16:24.233 --> 16:26.406
I decided that...

16:26.569 --> 16:30.244
rosé would be a
suitable compromise.

16:30.406 --> 16:33.000
My mum is gonna
have kittens.

16:33.159 --> 16:37.380
She resolutely refuses
to embrace any non-British grub.

16:37.538 --> 16:39.085
She does that whole
expat Marmite

16:39.248 --> 16:41.171
and baked bean thing.
Well,

16:41.334 --> 16:43.428
I think if you can swallow
Marmite,

16:43.586 --> 16:45.634
then you can manage minke whale.

16:45.796 --> 16:47.798
Okay, just don't tell her
it's whale, Markus.

16:47.965 --> 16:49.842
See if she likes it
and then say.

16:50.009 --> 16:51.852
Okay.

16:52.011 --> 16:53.854
Want some stew, Mum?

16:54.013 --> 16:56.186
Hmm?

16:56.349 --> 16:58.647
Thank you.

17:00.228 --> 17:02.071
Oh, hello, Markus.

17:02.230 --> 17:03.482
Doc.

17:03.648 --> 17:07.198
Markus has brought a starter.

17:08.319 --> 17:10.992
So, Margaret.

17:11.155 --> 17:15.410
I hear you were brought in
to check up on Frank Sutter.

17:15.576 --> 17:17.829
I'm not surprised
they arrested him.

17:17.994 --> 17:19.838
He's a violent man.

17:19.997 --> 17:22.500
I don't talk
about my patients.

17:22.666 --> 17:24.044
Shirley is the one for gossip.

17:24.210 --> 17:26.463
Oh, you're wrong
about that.

17:26.628 --> 17:28.631
Shirley
doesn't gossip.

17:28.798 --> 17:30.391
She tells everybody what
is happening in town.

17:30.550 --> 17:32.473
She doesn't exaggerate
or embellish,

17:32.635 --> 17:34.683
and everybody trusts her.

17:34.845 --> 17:36.847
I noticed this, and
I understood something,

17:37.014 --> 17:38.857
something quite
exceptional.

17:39.016 --> 17:43.271
In this town, your daughter is
the one person everybody loves.

17:51.946 --> 17:53.823
How's your whale, Mum?

18:20.850 --> 18:23.023
<i>Taq</i> polymerase.

18:23.185 --> 18:28.567
This is going
into PCR for four hours.

18:28.733 --> 18:29.985
Can you prep
the eyebrow follicle?

18:30.151 --> 18:32.119
We'll run it alongside.
Yep.

18:32.278 --> 18:35.532
They do not look right,
these reindeer fetuses.

18:35.698 --> 18:36.950
What is wrong with them?

18:37.116 --> 18:39.164
It's hermaphroditism.

18:39.327 --> 18:42.957
Male and female sex organs
developing simultaneously.

18:43.122 --> 18:44.715
They're all
spontaneous aborts.

18:44.874 --> 18:47.969
What is causing this?
Well,

18:48.127 --> 18:49.970
that's what we're working
to find out.

18:58.929 --> 19:01.398
<i>Are you in any pain, Frank?</i>

19:09.565 --> 19:10.817
Did you know Professor
Charles Stoddart?

19:10.983 --> 19:13.077
No.
You never met him?

19:13.235 --> 19:15.329
Never.
Okay.

19:15.488 --> 19:17.536
Didn't know him, never met him,
didn't kill him.

19:17.698 --> 19:21.453
Can you tell me how your
T-shirt got covered in blood?

19:21.619 --> 19:23.292
My little boy was sick.

19:23.454 --> 19:26.128
Dr. Allerdyce diagnosed mumps.

19:26.290 --> 19:29.134
Liam had been sick in bed
for two days.

19:29.293 --> 19:32.638
Friday night I was at home
with him all evening.

19:32.797 --> 19:34.799
Mm-hmm. I went to his
bedroom to check on him.

19:34.965 --> 19:37.559
He'd gotten up out of bed
and was lying on the floor.

19:37.718 --> 19:40.016
I picked him up. I noticed
that the swelling in his throat

19:40.179 --> 19:41.897
had gone down
and he was covered in blood.

19:42.056 --> 19:43.899
The swelling had ruptured.

19:44.058 --> 19:46.060
I carried him
to the bathroom.

19:46.227 --> 19:48.571
He was dopey,
half-awake.

19:48.729 --> 19:50.231
I put him
in the shower,

19:50.398 --> 19:52.651
checked him all over.

19:52.817 --> 19:56.697
He started talking for the first
time since he'd been ill.

19:56.862 --> 19:59.786
I gave him a wash
and put him back to bed.

19:59.949 --> 20:01.792
The T-shirt I was wearing
was covered in blood.

20:01.951 --> 20:04.204
It was ruined,
so I threw it in the bin.

20:04.370 --> 20:07.044
Didn't think about it.
It was just a T-shirt.

20:07.206 --> 20:09.550
Jules came home.

20:09.709 --> 20:12.963
Liam was seeming a lot better.

20:13.129 --> 20:16.099
She made macaroni and cheese
for the three of us.

20:20.219 --> 20:22.688
So the blood

20:22.847 --> 20:24.895
that was all over the T-shirt,
then, was your son's blood?

20:25.057 --> 20:28.186
Yes. Okay. So where did
that blood come from?

20:28.352 --> 20:30.525
From lacerations,
from cuts, from... what?

20:30.688 --> 20:32.941
I told you,
the swelling had ruptured.

20:33.107 --> 20:34.233
The swelling in
his throat...

20:34.400 --> 20:36.027
Yes.
had ruptured?

20:36.193 --> 20:38.070
Yes.

20:39.363 --> 20:42.207
That's a lot of blood.

20:42.366 --> 20:45.711
What's your point? Well, the point is
that that's so much blood and then

20:45.870 --> 20:48.714
the bleeding ceased,
just out of the blue,

20:48.873 --> 20:51.046
which is unusual.

20:51.208 --> 20:53.506
But he was hemorrhaging,

20:53.669 --> 20:55.512
and then it just stopped.

20:55.671 --> 20:57.264
And then he was fine,

20:57.423 --> 20:59.221
and then he ate
macaroni and cheese.

20:59.383 --> 21:01.260
That's unusual.

21:06.807 --> 21:09.026
Why did you leave the Army?

21:09.185 --> 21:12.109
I'd done five years
in Afghanistan.

21:12.271 --> 21:15.115
I missed my wife.
I missed my son.

21:15.274 --> 21:16.947
So you brought them here.

21:17.109 --> 21:18.361
That's right.

21:18.527 --> 21:20.621
But now you and your wife
are separated.

21:20.780 --> 21:23.909
And that's none
of your business.

21:24.074 --> 21:26.122
Fair enough.

21:28.287 --> 21:30.665
You know, I look
at pictures of, uh,

21:30.831 --> 21:33.584
helicopter squadrons
in the British Army,

21:33.751 --> 21:36.504
and I see all these
white, freckled...

21:36.670 --> 21:39.344
uh, Hooray Harry...

21:39.507 --> 21:41.350
or Henry or
whatever-whatever it is...

21:41.509 --> 21:44.683
fellas, you know, British
Army officer class.

21:44.845 --> 21:46.438
But what I...
You know what I don't see?

21:46.597 --> 21:48.144
I don't see black faces.

